We can, should, and must do more for safe mobility, a fundamental human right. People should never have to risk their lives to get pizza and go to Walmart with their children. That’s my mission for tomorrow and the coming decades.
This is a nation where 40,000 people die every year on the roads. This is a nation where 40,000 lives are irreparably destroyed by our transportation networks. One every thirteen minutes.

Think of what you would do, practically, in the designs you build. Think of your grandmother, of your little boy, of your mother, of your friend who is blind, of your loved ones who rely on public transportation to get around. Think of the users, and think of their safety.

Raquel’s story should be a reminder to transportation professionals everywhere. In everything we do, think of her and her children. Think of Austell Road and the legal expectation that people do what no person will ever do.

This wasn’t a secret. A reporter assigned to Raquel’s story even felt the need to wear a safety vest on the sidewalk at the site of the crash. There were energy and funds to prosecute; where was the same zeal to correct known safety issues before this preventable tragedy? https://t.co/6L9gNtdERK

Safety programs should be proactive. Streets with bus service will have people trying to cross. Multilane roads are inherently unsafe for people crossing. A.J. should not have died. That street was not safe.

The road system owner should be responsible for safety. The engineers that designed Austell Road are responsible for A.J.’s death on a street fundamentally unsafe. Laws that require people to do unreasonable things do not absolve the government of responsibility.
Safe mobility should be a human right. Streets that serve transit but that legally require people to walk fifteen minutes out of their way just to cross are not safe.

The great @PeterFurth has three values that all transportation professionals should take to heart.

1) Safe mobility is a human right.

2) The road system owner should be responsible for safety.

3) Safety programs should be proactive and address risks before they cause death.

For more than three years, Raquel Nelson had to relive that night when traffic violence took her son’s life. For more than three years, internet commenters and government prosecutors alike didn’t let her forget the terrible thing she did that any one of us would have done, too.

In October 2011, she appealed and the reckless conduct charge was dropped. In the spring of 2012, another appeal was denied. The case went all the way to the Georgia Supreme Court. More than three years passed before all criminal charges were formally dropped.
These jurors, middle-class whites who did not ride public transit, were not her peers. “None had ever been in Nelson’s shoes,” writes David Goldberg for T4America.
“Just one juror admitted to ever having ridden a public bus, though in response to a subsequent question, a few said they’d taken a bus to Braves games.”
“During jury questioning, none of the jurors who would eventually convict Nelson raised their hands when asked if they relied on public transportation,” Radley Balko of the Huffington Post wrote.
Nelson was found guilty in July 2011 of second-degree vehicular homicide, jaywalking, and reckless conduct. She was sentenced to a year’s probation and 40 hours of community service.

Three years in jail for jaywalking, reckless conduct, and vehicular homicide threatened against the mother of a child killed by a hit-and-run driver. Who had been drinking. Who was only jailed for six months.

Meanwhile, Raquel Nelson, frequent volunteer at school events and grief-stricken mother of three young children, was charged with vehicular homicide because she was not crossing at a crosswalk. She faced up to three years in jail.

Guy admitted to the hit-and-run that ended A.J.’s life and shattered Raquel’s world, pleaded guilty, and served six months in jail. He killed a four-year-old, fled the scene, and served six months in jail.

Jerry Guy had been drinking before getting behind the wheel of his van. He was on painkillers. He was partially blind in one eye. He had been convicted of two previous hit and run incidents. He killed A.J., the four-year-old boy carrying the goldfish. Jerry Guy never stopped.
“For some odd reason, I guess he saw the girl and decided to run out behind her. I said, ‘Stop, A.J.,’ and he was in the middle of the street so I said keep going. That’s when we all got hit.”

“One girl ran across the street,” Nelson said of what happened next. Raquel judges that there isn’t enough time for her and her family, tired and present-laden, to go. She decides to wait, holding her kids’ hands.

Nelson and her family get off the bus with a group of people. Several of them, including the family, start crossing at the bus stop. They make it to the median. Some in the group see a gap in traffic and start to go.
Imagine how exhausted the family must have been. You sure as hell wouldn’t walk fifteen minutes out of the way just to cross the street.

What would you do? What would any reasonable person do? You’d just cross the street to get home. You’d carefully wait for gaps in traffic. You’d look both ways. You’d run across the street. But damnit, you’d just want to get home.

The “legal” choice? Walk the 0.5+ mile (15 minute) round trip to the nearest “safe” crossing and back along Austell Road just to get home, directly across the street from where she started. All with her young children after an afternoon spent shopping. https://t.co/y4JJrou89E

And yet, Raquel Nelson’s bus dropped her and her family off at the sidewalk on the right side of this image, where people are standing. Her destination was her home, directly across, on the other side of the street. https://t.co/9hwGoP8PDw
Streets with transit service should be crossable.

Which users frequently end up on the opposite side of the street from where they’re going? That’s right—the riders of the street’s #30 bus. If you board the bus on your side of the street, you very likely get off on the opposite side of the street. That’s how it works.

Austell Road is wide for cars, but the sidewalks are barely wider than the absolute minimum. If you’re unlucky enough to be on the wrong side of the street, your options to cross are at infrequent crosswalks at stoplights or scurrying across five lanes of 45 mph traffic. https://t.co/HWM4guqocF

The family relied on public transportation to get around. On their way home, Raquel missed the bus. The next didn’t come for an hour. They waited for an hour. By the time they reached their stop, at their home on Austell Road, it was dark.

They had pizza and went to Wal-Mart. 

A.J. got a goldfish, which he carried in a plastic bag.

Raquel Nelson, a single mom and student at Kennesaw State University, took her three young children (Tyler, 9, A.J., 4, and Lauryn, 3) shopping from their home in Marietta, Georgia. Three of the family members had birthdays soon, and their trip was to celebrate.
